  "doc_id": "5042",
  "text": ", and the energy shift ℜe[Σ(ǫ k )] of the electron. There are two kinds of self-energy function in the description of a superconductor, usually labeled normal and anomalous. The normal component has the same meaning as in an ordinary metal, whereas the anomalous one is directly related to the opening of the gap due to the formation of Cooper pairs. These are closely related because the scattering rate and distortion of the electron bands due to the electron-phonon coupling depend strongly on the superconducting gap, and vice versa. This interdependence is accounted for by the so-called Eliashberg equations, which must be solved self-consistently [CITATION_1] .",
